===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Originally {{liushu|p|adj=1|nocap=1}} in the oracle bone script. The ancient Chinese regarded the rainbow as a two-headed dragon, as in an oracle-bone divination inscription:
{{zh-x|有 出 虹 自 北 飲 于 河。|A rainbow came forth from the north and drank from the River.|ref=oracle-bone inscription|CL|collapsed=y}}

In the seal script, it has become a {{Han compound|虫|工|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=insect; creature|nocap=1}}.

===Etymology===
Probably non-Sino-Tibetan; compare {{cog|hmx-mie-pro|*kluŋᴬ||rainbow}}, {{cog|th|รุ้ง||rainbow}}, {{cog|za|duzdoengz|duz'''doengz'''|rainbow}}, {{m|za|saidoengz|sai'''doengz'''|rainbow}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

{{zh-ref|Benedict (1986)}} and {{zh-ref|Carr (1990)}} relate this to {{och-l|龍|dragon}} and {{och-l|紅|red}}. {{zh-ref|Ferlus (2013)}} relates this to {{och-l|江|river}}, {{och-l|洚|flood}}{{,}} and {{och-l|龍|dragon}}, and posits that these words are derived from a root {{m|und|*-roŋ}}, with meanings related to moving water.

